:"d'Arques","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Mario, Luis, Fernando, Jorge, Armando, Ana, Joaquin, Julio, Marcos.  Portuguese Joao, Joaquim, Paulo, Henrique, Lourenco, Seraphine, Vasco.","Catalan (<b>Marquès</b>); Spanish and southern French (<b>Marqués</b>): from Catalan <i>marquès</i>, Spanish and Occitan <i>marqués</i> ‘marquis’, words of French origin (see   Marquis  ), applied either as a nickname for someone who behaved like a marquis or as an occupational name for a servant in the household of a marquis.","Portuguese: patronymic from the personal name   Marcos  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marquis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Normand, Marcel, Fernand, Lucien, Rosaire, Andre, Armand, Camille, Cecile, Jacques, Francois.","French: from the title <i>marquis</i> ‘marquess’, applied as an ironic nickname to someone who behaved like a marquis or as a metonymic occupational name for a servant in the household of a marquis. The title, derived from an ancient Germanic word meaning ‘boundary’ (compare   March  ), originally referred to the governor of a border territory. Marquises did not form part of the original French feudal structure of nobility; the title was first adopted by the Counts of Toulouse because of their possessions in the border region beyond the Rhône. Compare   Markee   and   Markey  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>markis</i> ‘marquis, marquess, nobleman’ (Old French <i>marchis</i>); see also 1 above. The word is also found as a female personal name which may also be origin of the surname."]}]},{"name":"Yvette","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine diminutive form of   Yves  , now also established in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Yvette d'Arques was bor